<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: NEW DELHI; THE TALBOTT MISSION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 With U.S. relations with Pakistan and India at a low point, the State 
Department's No. 2 official jets to the region this week for some fence mending 
and horse trading. 
</P>
<P>
 The visit of Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, due in New Delhi on 
Wednesday and Islamabad on Friday, is intended to personify high-level White 
House commitment to the two countries, which have felt ignored by the Clinton 
Administration. 
</P>
<P>
 Washington is trying to broker a three-party deal to promote nuclear 
non-proliferation on the subcontinent. It wants to deliver F-16 fighters to 
Pakistan in exchange for a verifiable cap on Pakistan's nuclear program. 
</P>
<P>
 To win Indian assent, Talbott, a friend of President Clinton, may be carrying 
promises of greater Indian access to American-made high-tech wares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
