<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 1; Column 4; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
744 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
GRUMMAN STOCKHOLDERS SIT PRETTY AS NORTHROP GETS NEW LEASE ON LIFE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN SLOAN, NEWSDAY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 To understand why Northrop Corp. emerged the "winner" in the battle for 
control of Grumman Corp., you have to understand the difference between wanting 
something and having to have it. 
</P>
<P>
 Martin Marietta Corp., the giant defense contractor that has made some recent 
big acquisitions, wanted Grumman. But Northrop, which had missed out on some 
recent big deals, felt that it had to have Grumman. 
</P>
<P>
 And so it got Grumman -- but has to pay almost $300 million more than Martin 
Marietta was willing to pay. 
</P>
<P>
 These days, of course, the U.S. defense industry is shrinking, as the defense 
budget drops with the end of the Cold War. Martin having made several large 
acquisitions of other defense businesses, is big enough to stay in the game. 
Northrop, by contrast, was at the point where it had to buy something sizable, 
or risk getting gobbled up. 
</P>
<P>
 Nevertheless, the difference between what Martin was willing to pay and what 
Northrop was really willing to pay is almost shocking. 
</P>
<P>
 The takeover battle began four weeks ago when Martin and Grumman announced 
that Grumman had agreed to Martin's $55 a share, or about $1.87 billion, offer. 
Martin was unwilling to raise its price, even after Northrop surfaced with a 
$60 offer and ultimately prevailed over the weekend with a bid of $62, or about 
$2.1 billion. (That offer isn't to be confused with Northrop's previous $62 
offer, which expired last week.) 
</P>
<P>
 Northrop was willing to pay substantially more than $62 a share. According to 
Securities and Exchange Commission filings, Northrop would have paid $66 for 
Grumman if Martin had bid $64 or more. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition to what it's paying Grumman shareholders, Northrop is in effect 
also paying the $50 million "breakup fee" that Grumman has paid Martin for 
canceling the $55-a-share deal. That fee, which Grumman agreed to pay if 
someone topped Martin's offer and bought Grumman, works out to about $1.50 per 
Grumman share. 
</P>
<P>
 The combination of the $62 price and the breakup fee mean that Northrop will 
pay $290 million more for Grumman than Martin Marietta was willing to pay. 
</P>
<P>
 If you do the same exercise with the $66 price that Northrop was willing to 
pay, Northrop's cost (including the fee) would have been $425 million above 
what Martin was willing to pay. 
</P>
<P>
 Neither Northrop nor Martin Marietta would say anything substantive about 
these different valuations on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 This is the second time that Northrop has broken up a Martin deal, snatching a 
property away. The other time was about two years ago, when Northrop was part 
of a group that broke up a deal that Martin and its partner, Lockheed Corp., 
had made for LTV Aerospace. LTV was in bankruptcy at the time, and Aerospace 
creditors were so upset by Martin's price that they managed to get a bidding 
contest started. Martin was unwilling to raise its bid much, and lost. 
</P>
<P>
 Northrop says its piece of LTV Aerospace has been very profitable, and that 
it's been a terrific deal. Whether Grumman will be a terrific deal remains to 
be seen. 
</P>
<P>
 If Grumman's projections of its future profits are accurate, Northrop will do 
OK, even at a cost of $63.50 a share. But Martin contends those projections are 
too high. Obviously, Northrop's analysis of Grumman's value gives more weight 
to these projections than Martin's does. That's the only way to justify what 
Northrop is paying. 
</P>
<P>
 The real winners of this takeover battle are Grumman's shareholders. A month 
ago, they owned a $40 stock. Now, they've got a $62 cash offer that should be 
completed before the month is out. You can argue that the holders would have 
gotten more than $62 if the Grumman board had bargained better. But considering 
that Martin refused to bid more than $55, Grumman holders should feel lucky to 
get $62. What would Grumman's board have done if Northrop had cut its offer to 
$58? Taken Martin's $55 offer? Not likely. 
</P>
<P>
 Northrop stockholders have to wonder. Before this deal, Northrop was an 
attractive takeover target. But after buying Grumman for $290 million more than 
the price at which Martin valued Grumman, Northrop will be saddled with a 
fairly heavy debt burden. That makes Northrop a much less appealing takeover 
candidate, despite the wishful Wall Street thinking about Martin taking over 
the Northrop-Grumman combination sometime in the future. 
</P>
<P>
 So Northrop has made the deal it felt it had to have. That was the easy part. 
Now, for the hard part: making the deal work. 
</P>
<P>
 * WINNING BIDDER: Northrop wins the auction for Grumman. A1 
</P>
</TEXT>
