<HEADLINE>
<P>
PIERCE STUDENT FACES RAPE, BEATING CHARGES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOSH MEYER and KAY HWANGBO, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 19-year-old Pierce College student faces rape charges for allegedly holding 
his ex-girlfriend against her will for three days, raping her repeatedly and 
beating her so severely with a pipe that patches of her skin came off, 
authorities said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 Michael Lim of Woodland Hills was arrested about 8 p.m. Sunday night near a 
Vons market at Ventura and Topanga Canyon boulevards, after he allegedly 
started hitting the woman in front of witnesses, according to Lt. George Rock 
of the Los Angeles Police Department's West Valley Division. 
</P>
<P>
 Several onlookers subdued Lim and held him for police officers, who arrested 
him on suspicion of felony spousal beating and rape, Rock said. The 23-year-old 
woman, who was not married to Lim but had lived briefly with him at his Warner 
Center Apartments unit, told police she had moved out because of physical 
abuse, Rock said. 
</P>
<P>
 When authorities took the woman to a local hospital so she could be examined, 
they said, they found that she was severely bruised from the waist down, and 
that she had been beaten by something resembling a metal pipe so harshly that 
muscle tissue was visible in many places. 
</P>
<P>
 "One veteran sergeant at the scene said it was the most severe beating he had 
witnessed in 20 years of police work," Rock said. "The injuries are very 
serious. Her skin actually was beaten off by whatever object she was beaten 
with. You are talking about raw skin tissue." 
</P>
<P>
 Because detectives believed Lim's parents to be wealthy enough to post 
significant bail, they took the unusual step of asking a judge to deny him bail 
pending a hearing. The judge agreed, and Lim was ordered held pending 
arraignment, scheduled for today. 
</P>
<P>
 "All we know is that we were informed that the suspect comes from a wealthy, 
influential family," Rock said. "Because of that we asked for a bail deviation, 
due to the severity and multitude of the crimes, and the apparent ability of 
the family to bail the suspect out." 
</P>
<P>
 Authorities said the woman had been living apart from Lim but had accompanied 
him back to the apartment in the 5500 block of Owensmouth Avenue late last 
week. There, police said, Lim held her against her will and subjected her to 
repeated beatings and rapes. 
</P>
<P>
 Police said the woman arrived from Korea a month ago. 
</P>
<P>
 Authorities refused to disclose at which hospital the woman was being treated, 
but said she was undergoing treatment for severe bruising. Detective Harry 
Hollywood, who is investigating the case, said the woman was bruised from her 
waistline to her feet. 
</P>
<P>
 "He held her for three days, during which time the suspect beat her with a 
metal pipe and sexually assaulted her," Hollywood said. 
</P>
<P>
 Authorities are continuing to investigate the case, and may ask that 
additional charges be filed against Lim, Rock said. 
</P>
<P>
 Lim had been living at the apartment complex since August, according to 
assistant manager Sandy Gay. She said Lim had been renting a one-bedroom unit 
at $825 a month, and was a "good resident" who never caused problems other than 
paying rent 20 days late on one occasion. 
</P>
<P>
 She said Lim was a Pierce College student and that his lease was co-signed by 
his father, Robert Y. Lim, who identified himself as a contracting specialist 
for the U. S. Army, stationed in Korea. 
</P>
<P>
 "Nobody's reported any unusual goings-on here," Gay said. "If it was something 
violent, it would be easy to hear." 
</P>
<P>
 A friend of Lim's also said he was surprised by the allegations. 
</P>
<P>
 "He was a nice guy. I'm kind of surprised," said Sung J. Lim, 18, a Tarzana 
resident who said he attended classes with Lim. The two are not related. 
</P>
<P>
 Sung Lim said he used to get together with Lim about twice a week but that he 
had not seen him for the past month or two. The friend said that Lim, who 
drives a Mitsubishi sports car, enjoyed participating in sports, working out in 
the apartment gym and relaxing with friends. 
</P>
<P>
 "I seriously don't think he was the type with a temper at all," Sung Lim said. 
"He was the quiet type." 
</P>
<P>
 Josh Meyer is a Times staff writer. Kay Hwangbo is a special correspondent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
