<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEW LAW IN ORANGE REQUIRES FIRE-RETARDANT ROOFS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Property owners must begin complying April 21 with a new city ordinance that 
requires new roofs be made from fire-retardant materials. 
</P>
<P>
 The ordinance, which was unanimously approved by the City Council in March, 
was drafted in response to the October, 1993, Stagecoach fire. 
</P>
<P>
 Seven homes in east Orange suffered significant damage, said fire officials, 
who added that the loss would have been less if the homes had used 
fire-retardant roofing materials. 
</P>
<P>
 The new ordinance also prohibits roofing over wood shakes or wood shingles. 
The ordinance applies only to new construction and homeowners putting on new 
roofs. 
</P>
